5. Coordinator Distribution
5.1 Strategy
The distribution function does not modify the COLLECT clause. The shard receives the same COLLECT command the user wrote - FIELDS, DEDUP, SORTBY, and LIMIT are unchanged.

Both shard and coordinator run the same Add() pipeline (Section 6.1). The only difference is in Finalize(): the shard serializes both the projected FIELDS values and the sort key values for each entry (the coordinator needs them to sort), while the coordinator outputs only the projected FIELDS.

5.2 Example:
User writes:



FT.AGGREGATE idx:fruits *
  LOAD *
  GROUPBY 1 @color
    REDUCE COLLECT 10 FIELDS 1 @sweetness SORTBY 2 @__score DESC LIMIT 0 2 AS top_fruits
Shard receives the identical command. The shard's Finalize() serializes each entry as: @sweetness sweetness_value (FIELDS) + @__score score_value (sort key, auxiliary). The coordinator deserializes both, uses @__score to sort, and outputs only @sweetness to the user.

6. Pipeline (Shard & Coordinator)
Both shard and coordinator use the same heap-based accumulation. On each Add() call (one per document in the group), the reducer captures the projected fields and sort keys, then inserts into a bounded min-max heap (mm_heap_t). The Add() logic is identical on both sides - the only difference is in Finalize() (see 6.2).

6.1 Add()
Capture sort key values from the source row.

Capture projected field values from the source row (IncrRef all RSValue* - they must survive the row wipe between documents).

If DEDUP is enabled: scan existing heap entries for a duplicate (same projected fields). If a duplicate is found, keep the entry with the better sort key (skip-or-replace). This ensures each unique projected value is represented by its best-ranked document.

Insert into the bounded heap.

Steps 2–4 only execute if the entry would make it into the heap (i.e., it's better than the current worst, or the heap is not full).

6.2 Finalize()
Pop all entries from the heap via repeated mmh_pop_max() - yields entries in sorted order (best → worst).

Apply LIMIT: skip first offset entries, return the next count.

Shard Finalize: for each surviving entry, build a flat KV array from fieldNames[] + projected[], and also serialize sort key values as auxiliary data (the coordinator needs them to sort).

Coordinator Finalize: for each surviving entry, build a flat KV array from fieldNames[] + projected[] only. Sort key values are not included in the user-facing output.

6.3 Coordinator Merge
The coordinator runs the same heap pipeline. The difference is the input: instead of raw documents, each Add() receives entries from a shard's COLLECT output (the alias column contains an array of KV entries). The coordinator unwraps these entries and inserts them into its own bounded heap.

6.4 Tie-Breaking
